rf with hold-out validation

This level of imbalance (5.2:1) is moderate—not extreme but definitely significant enough to impact your model’s performance:

Biased Predictions: Tree models trained on imbalanced data tend to favor the majority class because predicting the majority class leads to higher accuracy. Performance Metrics Misinterpretation: Accuracy becomes misleading. A model that always predicts the majority class would achieve 84% accuracy in our example, but be useless for identifying minority class instances. Impact on Tree Structure: Decision trees optimize for purity measures (Gini impurity or entropy), which can lead them to ignore minority class patterns. Cross-Validation Effects: The imbalance may be distributed unevenly across CV folds, contributing to the performance gap you observed.

set.seed(123)
train_indices <- createDataPartition(df_e$Attrition, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)

train_data <- df_e[train_indices, ]
test_data <- df_e[-train_indices, ]

attrition_table <- table(train_data$Attrition)

findout: ntree, nodesize, parameter does not bring significant change to the model result but the change of threshold has apparent impacts on the trade-off between accuracy and senstivity. Otherwise, In order to address the class imbalance problem, i have add class weight parameter (1:5.2) when building the model. It shows counterintuitive result that shows even lower performances especially the obvious drop of AUC value.The potential reason is that getting high sensitivity will also cause overfit to the minority class by adjusting the class weight.

# Get predicted probabilities
probs <- predict(rf_model, newdata = test_data, type = "prob")[,2]

# Calculate metrics across different thresholds
thresholds <- seq(0.1, 0.5, length.out = 100)
results <- data.frame(threshold = thresholds, sensitivity = NA, specificity = NA, 
                     accuracy = NA, balanced_accuracy = NA)

for(i in 1:length(thresholds)) {
  preds <- ifelse(probs > thresholds[i], "Yes", "No")
  results$sensitivity[i] <- sum(preds == "Yes" & test_data$Attrition == "Yes") / sum(test_data$Attrition == "Yes")
  results$specificity[i] <- sum(preds == "No" & test_data$Attrition == "No") / sum(test_data$Attrition == "No")
  results$accuracy[i] <- sum(preds == test_data$Attrition) / length(test_data$Attrition)
  results$balanced_accuracy[i] <- (results$sensitivity[i] + results$specificity[i]) / 2
}

# Find optimal threshold balancing high sensitivity with reasonable accuracy
optimal_idx <- which.max(results$sensitivity * 0.55 + results$accuracy * 0.45)
optimal_threshold <- thresholds[optimal_idx]

# Plot the metrics
plot(thresholds, results$sensitivity, type="l", col="blue", ylim=c(0, 1),
     main="Performance Metrics vs Threshold", xlab="Threshold", ylab="Value")
lines(thresholds, results$specificity, col="orange")
lines(thresholds, results$accuracy, col="green")
lines(thresholds, results$balanced_accuracy, col="purple")
abline(v=optimal_threshold, lty=2)
legend("topright", legend=c("Sensitivity", "Specificity", "Accuracy", "Balanced Accuracy", "Selected Threshold"),
       col=c("blue", "orange", "green", "purple", "black"), lty=c(1,1,1,1,2))

# Plot ROC curve and display AUC value

## Setting direction: controls < cases

     xlab = "False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity)", 
     ylab = "True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)")

# Create performance metrics table including threshold and AUC
threshold <- optimal_threshold  # Optimal threshold
probs <- predict(rf_model, newdata = test_data, type = "prob")[,2]
predictions <- ifelse(probs > threshold, "Yes", "No")
metrics <- c(Threshold = threshold,
            Sensitivity = sum(predictions == "Yes" & test_data$Attrition == "Yes") / sum(test_data$Attrition == "Yes"),
            Specificity = sum(predictions == "No" & test_data$Attrition == "No") / sum(test_data$Attrition == "No"),
            Accuracy = sum(predictions == test_data$Attrition) / length(test_data$Attrition),
            F1_Score = 2 * sum(predictions == "Yes" & test_data$Attrition == "Yes") / 
                      (2 * sum(predictions == "Yes" & test_data$Attrition == "Yes") + 
                       sum(predictions == "Yes" & test_data$Attrition == "No") + 
                       sum(predictions == "No" & test_data$Attrition == "Yes")),
            AUC = as.numeric(auc(roc(test_data$Attrition, probs))))

Now to adjust the overfitting by adding k-fold cross-validation and SMOTE sampling. Have tested k-fold value (5, 10, 15), fail to recognize significant change in performance so keep k-fold = 10. Changing the ntree parameter (50, 100, 200, 1000), fail to observe significant change in performance for most result statistics. There is a slightly increase in accuracy while increase ntree alot (200 to 1000) so keep the ntree value at 100 to ensure efficient.

# Set up training control with k-fold cross-validation
set.seed(123)
train_control <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",              # Cross-validation
  number = 10,                # 10 folds
  sampling = "smote",         # SMOTE sampling
  classProbs = TRUE,          # Compute class probabilities
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,  # For ROC, Sens, Spec
  savePredictions = "final"   # Save predictions for ROC
)

# Train the Random Forest model with SMOTE sampling
rf_model_cv <- train(
  Attrition ~ .,
  data = train_data,
  method = "rf",              # Random Forest
  #metric = "ROC",             # Optimize based on ROC
  trControl = train_control,  # Use the training control with SMOTE
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(
    mtry = sqrt(ncol(train_data) - 1)  # Default mtry value
  ),
  ntree = 100,                # Number of trees
  nodesize = 3,               # Node size
  importance = TRUE           # Variable importance
)

text(1 - optimal_coords$specificity, optimal_coords$sensitivity, 
     labels = paste("Optimal\nThreshold =", round(optimal_threshold, 2)), 
     pos = 4, col = "red")

# Get cross-validation training accuracy from the model
cv_train_acc <- mean(rf_model_cv$pred[rf_model_cv$pred$mtry == rf_model_cv$bestTune$mtry,]$pred == 
                    rf_model_cv$pred[rf_model_cv$pred$mtry == rf_model_cv$bestTune$mtry,]$obs)

# Get test accuracy
cv_test_acc <- mean(predict(rf_model_cv, test_data) == test_data$Attrition)

# Calculate and print overfitting measure
cv_diff <- cv_train_acc - cv_test_acc
cat("\nCV+SMOTE model - Training accuracy:", round(cv_train_acc, 4), 
   "Test accuracy:", round(cv_test_acc, 4), 
   "Overfitting measure:", round(cv_diff, 4))
## 
## CV+SMOTE model - Training accuracy: 0.8641 Test accuracy: 0.8659 Overfitting measure: -0.0018

two models has Similar performance metrics but very different generalization. Both models have comparable performance metrics (accuracy, sensitivity, specificity).However, observe Dramatically different overfitting levels. The CV+SMOTE model will likely perform more consistently on new, unseen data Its predictions are more reliable because it learned generalizable patterns The basic RF model learned noise in the training data, making its predictions less trustworthy.

This difference in distributions reveals another key advantage of the CV+SMOTE approach: Better calibration: The CV+SMOTE model appears to use a wider range of probability values, suggesting it’s better calibrated (its confidence levels more accurately reflect actual probabilities). Honest uncertainty: The CV+SMOTE model shows more predictions with mid-range probabilities, indicating it “knows when it doesn’t know” - it expresses appropriate uncertainty when cases are ambiguous. Avoiding false confidence: The basic RF model makes very high-confidence predictions even though we know it’s overfitting. This suggests it may be falsely confident in many of its predictions. Decision boundary clarity: The CV+SMOTE model shows a clearer separation between classes (the bimodal distribution), which can make threshold selection more robust. This difference in probability distributions further confirms why the CV+SMOTE model is superior - it not only avoids overfitting but also produces better-calibrated probabilities that more accurately reflect the true uncertainty in the predictions. The basic RF model’s high-confidence predictions are concerning because they suggest it’s not properly expressing uncertainty, which can lead to overconfident and potentially incorrect decisions in practical applications.

library(pROC)
library(ggplot2)

# roc and optimized threshold
roc_obj <- roc(test_data$Attrition, pred_probs_basic1, levels = c("No", "Yes"))
## Setting direction: controls < cases
threshold_analysis <- coords(roc_obj, x = "all", ret = c("threshold", "sensitivity", "specificity"))
threshold_df <- as.data.frame(threshold_analysis)

best_threshold_df <- threshold_df[threshold_df$sensitivity >= 0.8, ]
best_threshold_df <- best_threshold_df[which.max(best_threshold_df$specificity), ]
optimal_threshold <- as.numeric(best_threshold_df$threshold)

# roc curve
roc_df <- data.frame(
  FPR = 1 - roc_obj$specificities,
  TPR = roc_obj$sensitivities,
  Threshold = roc_obj$thresholds
)

# plot
# 准备最佳点的数据框
best_point <- data.frame(
  FPR = 1 - as.numeric(best_threshold_df$specificity),
  TPR = as.numeric(best_threshold_df$sensitivity)
)

# 绘图
ggplot(roc_df, aes(x = FPR, y = TPR)) +
  geom_line(color = "steelblue", linewidth = 1.2) +
  geom_abline(linetype = "dashed", color = "grey") +
  geom_point(data = best_point, aes(x = FPR, y = TPR), color = "red", size = 3) +
  annotate("text", 
           x = best_point$FPR + 0.05, 
           y = best_point$TPR, 
           label = paste0("Best Threshold: ", round(optimal_threshold, 3),
                          "\nSens: ", round(best_point$TPR, 2),
                          "\nSpec: ", round(1 - best_point$FPR, 2)),
           hjust = 0, size = 4) +
  labs(title = "ROC Curve with Optimal Threshold Highlighted",
       subtitle = paste("AUC =", round(auc(roc_obj), 3)),
       x = "1 - Specificity (False Positive Rate)",
       y = "Sensitivity (True Positive Rate)") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14)
